      { heading: 'Turning Daily Sales Into Proof You Can Show Someone', level: 2 as const, body: 'AskBiz logs every sale automatically as it happens, which means that after even a few months of use, a trader has a genuine record of daily and monthly income without ever having sat down to build one on purpose. This is different from a notebook, which is hard for anyone outside the business to trust or even read, and different from trying to reconstruct six months of trading from memory when a bank asks for it. A trader applying for a small loan to move from Mupedzanhamo into a rented stall can show real numbers — average daily sales, monthly totals, seasonal patterns — that make the difference between being seen as a risk and being seen as a business with a track record.' },
      { heading: 'The Business Pulse Score as a Simple Health Check', level: 2 as const, body: 'Beyond raw sales figures, AskBiz gives every trader a daily Business Pulse score that reflects the overall health of the business — how consistent sales are, how well stock is managed, how much credit is outstanding. For a trader deciding whether they are actually ready to take on the fixed costs of a registered shop, watching that score stay strong over several months is a far more honest signal than simply feeling optimistic. It also gives something concrete to point to in a conversation with a potential business partner or family member being asked to help fund the move, since it is not just the trader\'s word that the business is doing well.' },
      { heading: 'What Registration Actually Requires, and Why Records Come First', level: 2 as const, body: 'Formalizing a business in Zimbabwe, even at a small scale, generally means registering with the Registrar of Companies or as a sole trader, and often engaging with ZIMRA once turnover crosses certain thresholds. None of that is fast or free, and traders who jump into registration before their records are in order often struggle to reconcile what they are declaring with what they can actually prove they earned. Traders who build the habit of tracking every sale through AskBiz well before registration find the transition far smoother, because the financial history already exists in a form that makes sense to a bank, a landlord, or a tax authority, rather than needing to be invented retroactively under pressure.' }
